THE AIRCRAFT COLLIDED WITH RISING TERRAIN DURING A CROSS-COUNTRY IN IMC 
WEATHER. NO FLIGHT PLAN WAS FILED FOR THE FLIGHT. NO WEATHER BRIEFING WAS 
OBTAINED BY THE PILOT BEFORE TAKEOFF. THE DISTANCE TO BE FLOWN WAS 72 
MILES AND THE PILOT FLEW THIS ROUTE ABOUT 3 TIMES A WEEK. THE FLIGHT GOT 
WITHIN 5 MILES OF DESTINATION BEFORE COLLIDING WITH THE TERRAIN AT 1200 
FEET MSL. THE MOUNTAIN TOPS IN THE AREA GO AS HIGH AS 2500 FEET MSL. THE PILOT 
WAS FLYING UP A CANYON IN LOW OVERCAST WEATHER CONDITIONS. 
